2022 was interesting….to say the least. But like any other year, it definitely came with good memories. Glad to be entering 2023 with a lot of positive vibes, surrounded by people I love and a roof over my head. Alhamdulillah. 

Happy new year! 🎆

When @projectlionheartsg reached out and asked if I want to be part of this, I was so excited! Being a wife to a civil servant is interesting and there are so many stories to tell. 

My husband, Zul, has been in the Singapore Civil Defence Force for the last seven years. In 2020, he was deployed to the medical unit as an ambulance driver. When the pandemic struck, my husband was on the frontlines helping with the surge in COVID-19 cases, and often had to take up extra shifts due to the high volume of calls. Back at home, I had to hold the fort and take care of our two sons on my own as schools were closed and visitors were not allowed during the circuit breaker period.

In 2021, I found out I was pregnant with my third son. My anxiety grew with every new wave that came and went. Not only was I concerned about the possibility of catching the virus while pregnant, I was also worried about the labour process. I was afraid I would have to go through the delivery without my husband by my side due to the safe management measures that were in place. Fortunately, restrictions were relaxed by the time my baby was due, and my husband was allowed to stay with me throughout the delivery. 

Our son will be turning one in a few months’ time, and he has brought so much hope and light to the family in these otherwise dark times. This whole episode has been an eye-opening experience for us. Every single second we have with each other is precious, and we’ve learnt not to take any of it for granted. 

If you are interested to experience the other inspiring stories and artworks, check out @projectlionheartsg! Their current exhibition is at Changi Airport until 11 Jan. 📍✈️

I felt like I just gave birth to this little guy and now he’s already one. 

My birth story with him is short but it felt like a long process because I fell when I was 36 weeks and the injury was not serious but too a long time to heal. So I gave birth with an injured tailbone and that was obviously not a nice feeling. He was quite big too. 

After labour, I could only lie down flat and couldn’t sit up or even turn to my side. So every time I had to eat or breastfeed, it was pure misery. I actually thought I was going to be like that forever. 😵‍💫 

I’m so happy to be able to stay home and care for him full time for the first year. Wasn’t easy but so fulfilling. 

Happy birthday, dimple boy. ❤️
